# Trivy waivers — neo4j image only (wired to the neo4j scan step in
# .github/workflows/ci.yml via the `trivyignores:` input; NOT applied to the
# pgvector or ollama scans, which stay strict).
#
# Context (Issue #2): the neo4j base image is pinned to
# neo4j:5.26.25-community-ubi10. Switching from the Debian (`-trixie`) base to
# Red Hat UBI-10 already eliminated all 14 HIGH/CRITICAL OS-package CVEs
# (including 2 CRITICAL gnutls) — those are NOT waived, they are fixed by the
# base choice. What remains are 6 HIGH CVEs in the netty jars that Neo4j 5.26.25
# bundles itself (netty 4.1.132.Final), plus 1 HIGH in the bundled Apache Shiro
# auth framework (shiro-core 2.1.0). They are identical across every base
# variant and cannot be fixed without a new Neo4j release that bumps the bundled
# jars (netty >= 4.1.135.Final; shiro-core >= 2.2.1). The netty waivers are
# below; the shiro waiver (CVE-2026-49268) is in its own section at the bottom.
#
# Why these are acceptable for THIS deployment (spec §6.7 accept-with-justification):
#   - Story Forge runs Neo4j bound to 127.0.0.1 only, single trusted user,
#     non-root container, no-new-privileges. There is no untrusted network peer.
#   - None of the six is data-disclosure or RCE. Most are denial-of-service
#     (resource exhaustion); one is an HTTP client-codec response-desync bug
#     reachable only when Neo4j acts as an outbound HTTP client against a
#     malicious server; one is an IPv6 subnet-*filter* bypass in netty's
#     access-control filtering — a mechanism this deployment does not use as a
#     security boundary (the loopback bind is the boundary); one silently disables
#     TLS hostname verification (MITM) but only when netty terminates TLS for an
#     untrusted peer — this deployment runs no public TLS. All require an untrusted
#     network peer this single-user 127.0.0.1 deployment never has.
#   - The first three are fixed in netty 4.1.133.Final (2026-05-04); the three
#     added 2026-06-10/2026-06-16 are fixed in netty 4.1.135.Final. Drop this file
#     the moment a Neo4j 5.26.x patch ships bundling >= 4.1.135.Final; a re-scan
#     should then pass clean with no waiver.
#
# All waivers across images are also indexed in infra/trivy/WAIVERS.md (the
# review register: fixed-in versions + drop conditions, checked periodically).
#
# Revisit: each Neo4j patch bump (next time the image tag is updated).

# CVE-2026-42583 — netty-codec (Lz4FrameDecoder): a stream of small LZ4 frames
# forces repeated large buffer allocation -> memory exhaustion (DoS). Fixed in
# 4.1.133.Final by enforcing maxDecompressedLength.
CVE-2026-42583

# CVE-2026-42584 — netty-codec-http (HttpClientCodec): response desynchronization
# mis-pairing pipelined HEAD/GET with 1xx responses (client-side parsing bug,
# not DoS). Not reachable: we do not drive Neo4j as an HTTP client.
CVE-2026-42584

# CVE-2026-42587 — netty-codec-http (HttpContentDecompressor): maxAllocation
# bypass via br/zstd/snappy Content-Encoding -> decompression-bomb DoS. Fixed in
# 4.1.133.Final.
CVE-2026-42587

# CVE-2026-44249 — netty-handler (IpSubnetFilterRule): IPv6 subnet-filter bypass
# via incorrect comparator masking (CWE-284/697). An access-control filter is
# evaded — not data-disclosure or RCE — and only matters where netty IP-filtering
# gates untrusted peers. This deployment binds Neo4j to 127.0.0.1 and does not use
# netty IP-filtering as a boundary, so there is nothing to bypass. Fixed in netty
# 4.1.135.Final (4.1.x branch; also 4.2.15.Final). (Verified vs GitHub Advisory DB.)
CVE-2026-44249

# CVE-2026-45416 — netty-handler (SniHandler): nine attacker-controlled bytes in a
# TLS ClientHello SNI trigger a pre-allocation of up to 16 MiB -> memory-exhaustion
# DoS (CWE-770). Reachable only against a TLS listener terminated by netty's
# SniHandler facing an untrusted client; Neo4j here runs without public TLS, bound
# to 127.0.0.1, trusted local client only. Fixed in netty 4.1.135.Final (also
# 4.2.15.Final). (Verified vs GitHub Advisory DB.)
CVE-2026-45416

# CVE-2026-50010 — netty-handler (SimpleTrustManagerFactory / X509TrustManagerWrapper):
# wrapping a plain X509TrustManager silently disables TLS hostname verification
# (GHSA-c653-97m9-rcg9), enabling MITM of a TLS peer. Reachable only where netty
# terminates/initiates TLS against an untrusted peer using a plain trust manager;
# Neo4j here runs without public TLS, bound to 127.0.0.1, single trusted local
# client — there is no untrusted TLS peer to impersonate. Fixed in netty
# 4.1.135.Final (also 4.2.15.Final). (Verified vs OSV / GitHub Advisory DB.)
CVE-2026-50010

# ── Bundled Apache Shiro (Neo4j's auth framework) — added 2026-06-19 ──
# CVE-2026-49268 — org.apache.shiro:shiro-core (shiro-core-2.1.0.jar): LDAP
# injection via insufficient escaping of RFC-2253 special characters when
# constructing a Distinguished Name (DN) in the DefaultLdapRealm class —
# potentially authentication bypass / user impersonation. Fixed in Shiro 2.2.1
# (also 3.0.0-alpha-2). (Verified vs the Apache Shiro security-reports page;
# the CVE is too fresh for NVD / the GitHub Advisory DB as of 2026-06-19.)
# NOT REACHABLE here: the flaw is in Shiro's *LDAP authentication realm*, but
# Neo4j LDAP/AD auth is an ENTERPRISE-only feature — this deployment runs Neo4j
# COMMUNITY (neo4j:5.26.x-community-ubi10) with only the native auth realm, so
# DefaultLdapRealm is never configured or instantiated; there is no LDAP
# directory and no DN is ever built from user input. Defence in depth: Neo4j is
# bound to 127.0.0.1, single trusted local user, native NEO4J_AUTH basic auth.
# Bundled by Neo4j like the netty jars above — neo4j 5.26.26 (and the unsoaked
# .27) still ship shiro-core 2.1.0 (verified by a local Trivy scan 2026-06-19),
# so no image bump fixes it yet.
# Drop when: a soaked (>= 7-day) Neo4j 5.26.x patch bundles shiro-core >= 2.2.1
# (re-scan to confirm CVE-2026-49268 is gone); checked at each neo4j tag bump.
CVE-2026-49268
